{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":32198,"record_hash":"sha256:9b1e25d29debce92bf9d2219a1ba10d96424c8f5d2e19df4e78b5d0b4d9b3bc0","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:57:03.407Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 751fea\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 667\nOutput:\nlocal ref:  refs/meta/local/agentlog\nremote ref: refs/meta/agentlog\nmatches key:\n  key == \"gitbutler:agent-sessions\"\n  key starts with \"gitbutler:agent-session:\"\n```\n\nExact function names can be decided in `git-meta`, but the important API\nproperty is that key scope is command-scoped, not achieved by mutating the\nuser's persistent `meta:filter` or `meta:local:filter` configuration.\n\nScoped materialization is also required. Materializing `refs/meta/agentlog` must\nonly reconcile keys matched by the agentlog scope. Keys outside that matcher are\nnot part of the ref, so their absence from the remote tree must not delete or\noverwrite unrelated local GitMeta data.\n\nFor the POC, scoped serialization can rebuild the scoped ref from current\nSQLite state and does not need its own schema or incremental marker. It also\nmust not advance the default all-metadata materialization marker.\n\nThe scoped data mechanics belong in `git-meta`. The orchestration policy\nbelongs in `but-agentlog` for the POC: fetch if the ref exists, serialize,\nmaterialize, re-serialize, push, and retry on non-fast-forward. If that proves\ngenerally useful, it can be promoted into GitMeta later.\n\n## GitMeta API Design Bias\n\n`MetadataScope` should be a general GitMeta library concept, not an agentlog-only\nspecial case. Other consumers should be able to define a named key scope, local\nref, remote ref, and key matcher without depending on GitButler vocabulary.\n\nAt the same time, do not build a broad framework before there is pressure for\nit. The first implementation should be rooted in the concrete agentlog use\ncase:\n\n- one named scope\n- exact key matching\n- one local ref and one remote ref\n- scoped serialize/materialize primitives without new bookkeeping\n- normal Git fetch/push transport in the GitButler caller\n- bounded non-fast-forward retry in the GitButler caller\n\nPrefer APIs that make this concrete use case easy to write correctly, then leave\n1. Add `MetadataScope` to `git-meta`.\n   - It should carry a name, local ref suffix/ref, remote ref suffix/ref, and a\n     key matcher.\n   - It should be general enough for non-GitButler callers.\n\n2. Add scoped serialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Serialize only keys matched by the `MetadataScope`.\n   - Write `refs/meta/local/<scope-name>` for the agentlog scope.\n   - Do not mutate persistent filter rules to achieve this.\n   - Do not add scoped schema/bookkeeping until it has behavioral value.\n\n3. Add scoped materialization in `git-meta`.\n   - Materialize only keys matched by the `MetadataScope`.\n   - Missing keys outside the scope must not affect local SQLite state.\n   - Missing remote ref means initial sync, not deletion.\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:57:03.407Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}